Drew Blythe Barrymore (born February 22, 1975) is a multifaceted American talent, recognized for her extensive work as an actress, producer, talk show host, and businesswoman. Her lineage traces back to the esteemed [Barrymore family](/Barrymore_family), a dynasty steeped in theatrical and cinematic history. Throughout her career, Barrymore has garnered a significant number of accolades, including prestigious honors such as a [Golden Globe Award](/Golden_Globe_Awards), an [Emmy Award](/Emmy_Awards), and a [BAFTA](/British_Academy_Film_Awards). Her influence and impact were further acknowledged when she was named one of the [100 most influential people in the world](/Time_100) by [Time](/Time_(magazine)) in 2023, a testament to her enduring presence and cultural resonance.

Barrymore's initial ascent to fame was as a remarkable [child star](/Child_actor), most notably for her role in Steven Spielberg's iconic 1982 film [E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial](/E.T._the_Extra-Terrestrial). She solidified her status as a prominent figure in [Hollywood](/Hollywood) with a series of compelling performances in films that spanned various genres. Her early work included roles in [Firestarter](/Firestarter_(1984_film)) (1984), [Poison Ivy](/Poison_Ivy_(1992_film)) (1992), [Boys on the Side](/Boys_on_the_Side) (1995), and the quintessential slasher film [Scream](/Scream_(1996_film)) (1996). As she transitioned into more mature roles, Barrymore captivated audiences in films like the romantic fairy tale [Ever After](/Ever_After) (1998), the charming comedy [Never Been Kissed](/Never_Been_Kissed) (1999), and the action-packed [Charlie's Angels](/Charlie%27s_Angels_(2000_film)) franchise, including [Charlie's Angels: Full Throttle](/Charlie%27s_Angels:_Full_Throttle) (2003). Her on-screen chemistry with [Adam Sandler](/Adam_Sandler) became a reliable draw, leading to successful collaborations in [The Wedding Singer](/The_Wedding_Singer) (1998), [50 First Dates](/50_First_Dates) (2004), and [Blended](/Blended_(film)) (2014). Barrymore's filmography also features notable appearances in [Batman Forever](/Batman_Forever) (1995), the cult classic [Donnie Darko](/Donnie_Darko) (2001), the biographical thriller [Confessions of a Dangerous Mind](/Confessions_of_a_Dangerous_Mind_(film)) (2002), the musical comedy [Music and Lyrics](/Music_and_Lyrics) (2007), the ensemble romantic comedy [He's Just Not That Into You](/He%27s_Just_Not_That_Into_You_(film)) (2009), and the long-distance relationship dramedy [Going the Distance](/Going_the_Distance_(2010_film)) (2010).

Her prowess in television was recognized with a [Golden Globe Award for Best Actress in a Television Film](/Golden_Globe_Award_for_Best_Actress_%E2%80%93_Miniseries_or_Television_Film) for her poignant portrayal of [Edith Bouvier Beale](/Edith_Bouvier_Beale) in the HBO production [Grey Gardens](/Grey_Gardens_(2009_film)). She further captivated audiences as Sheila Hammond in the [Netflix](/Netflix) horror-comedy series [Santa Clarita Diet](/Santa_Clarita_Diet) (2017–2019), and has since transitioned to hosting the popular daytime talk show [The Drew Barrymore Show](/The_Drew_Barrymore_Show) (2020–present).

Beyond her acting career, Barrymore has established herself as a formidable entrepreneur. She is the founder of the production company [Flower Films](/Flower_Films), which has been instrumental in bringing several of her projects to fruition, including her directorial debut with [Whip It](/Whip_It_(film)) (2009). In 2013, she expanded her brand into the beauty industry with the launch of a cosmetics line under the Flower banner. Her business acumen extends to other ventures, including a line of wines, [7] homeware, and clothing. [8] Barrymore has also authored several books, four of which have achieved recognition as New York Times bestsellers. These include her memoir, *Little Girl Lost* (1990), and the photobook *Find It in Everything* (2014). [1] [9] [10]

## Early life

### Ancestry

Barrymore's origins are deeply entwined with the rich tapestry of the [Barrymore family](/Barrymore_family), a lineage of actors that has left an indelible mark on American theater and film. She was born Drew Blythe Barrymore on February 22, 1975, in [Culver City, California](/Culver_City,_California). Her parents were actor [John Drew Barrymore](/John_Drew_Barrymore) and aspiring actress Jaid Barrymore (born Ildikó Jaid Makó). [11] [12] Jaid Barrymore's own history is marked by resilience, having been born in a [displaced persons camp](/Displaced_persons_camps_in_post-World_War_II_Europe) in [Brannenburg](/Brannenburg), [West Germany](/West_Germany), to Hungarian refugees who had fled during [World War II](/World_War_II). [13] [14] Drew has three older half-siblings from her father's previous relationships, including the actor [John Blyth Barrymore](/John_Blyth_Barrymore). [15] Her parents' marriage concluded in divorce in 1984. [1]

In a notable appearance on [her talk show](/The_Drew_Barrymore_Show) in 2023, Barrymore shared the results of an [AncestryDNA](/AncestryDNA) test. The analysis indicated her genetic makeup was primarily European, with a surprising 6% [North Indian](/North_India) heritage. [16]

The Barrymore name is synonymous with acting excellence. Drew's paternal great-grandparents, [Maurice](/Maurice_Barrymore) and [Georgie Drew Barrymore](/Georgiana_Drew), along with [Maurice](/Maurice_Costello) and [Mae Costello](/Mae_Costello) (née Altschuk), and her paternal grandparents, [John Barrymore](/John_Barrymore) and [Dolores Costello](/Dolores_Costello), were all accomplished actors. [17] John Barrymore, in particular, is widely regarded as one of the most acclaimed actors of his era. [1] [18] Drew is also related to a constellation of other theatrical figures: she is the niece of [Diana Barrymore](/Diana_Barrymore), and the grandniece of [Lionel Barrymore](/Lionel_Barrymore), [Ethel Barrymore](/Ethel_Barrymore), and [Helene Costello](/Helene_Costello). [19] Further back, she is the great-great-granddaughter of the Irish-born actor [John](/John_Drew_(actor)) and the English-born actress [Louisa Lane Drew](/Louisa_Lane_Drew), both pillars of the stage. Her lineage also includes the celebrated Broadway idol [John Drew Jr.](/John_Drew_Jr.) and the pioneering [silent film](/Silent_film) actor, writer, and director [Sidney Drew](/Mr._%26_Mrs._Sidney_Drew). [20]

Her [godparents](/Godparent) include the legendary Italian actress [Sophia Loren](/Sophia_Loren) [21] and Anna Strasberg, the widow of acting guru [Lee Strasberg](/Lee_Strasberg). Barrymore has spoken of Anna Strasberg's profound influence, describing her as a "kind and nurturing" figure who played a significant role in her childhood. [22] Her godfather is none other than the visionary filmmaker [Steven Spielberg](/Steven_Spielberg). [23] [24] [25] [26]

The name "Drew" itself holds familial significance, being the maiden name of her paternal great-grandmother, Georgie Drew. Her middle name, "Blythe," is a nod to the birth surname (Blyth) of her great-grandfather, who later adopted the stage name Maurice Barrymore. [23] Barrymore's early life was profoundly shaped by the absence of her father, John Drew Barrymore, who left the family when she was just six months old. In her 1991 autobiography, *Little Girl Lost*, she recounted memories of an abusive father and a relationship characterized by infrequent contact and a lack of deep connection. [27]

### Childhood

Barrymore spent her formative years on Poinsettia Place in [West Hollywood, California](/West_Hollywood,_California), before relocating to [Sherman Oaks, Los Angeles](/Sherman_Oaks,_Los_Angeles) at the age of seven. In her 2015 memoir, *Wildflower*, she humorously noted her adoption of a "[valley girl](/Valley_girl)" accent, attributed to her upbringing in Sherman Oaks. A return to [West Hollywood](/West_Hollywood) marked her [emancipation](/Emancipation_of_minors) at the age of 14. [28] Her early education took place at Fountain Day School in West Hollywood and later at Country School. [29] The sudden blaze of stardom that accompanied her childhood was, unfortunately, intertwined with a notoriously tumultuous youth. She became a familiar face at the infamous [Studio 54](/Studio_54) as a young girl, and her burgeoning nightlife and constant partying became fodder for the media.

At the tender age of 13, she was admitted to [rehab](/Drug_rehabilitation) [1] [23] and subsequently spent eighteen months at Van Nuys Behavioral Health Hospital, an institution for individuals with mental health challenges. [30] A suicide attempt at 14 led to another stint in rehab, followed by a three-month period living with singer [David Crosby](/David_Crosby) and his wife. Crosby explained that Barrymore needed to be in an environment with people committed to sobriety. [27] This tumultuous period was candidly detailed in her autobiography, *Little Girl Lost*. Following a successful petition for emancipation in [juvenile court](/Juvenile_court), she secured her own apartment at the age of 15, marking a significant step toward independence. [27] [18]

## Career

### Early roles and breakthrough as a child actor (1976–1985)

Barrymore's journey into the spotlight began before she could even walk, appearing in a [dog food](/Dog_food) commercial at the age of eleven months. Her film debut was a minor role in [Altered States](/Altered_States), [1] but it was her enchanting performance as Gertie in Steven Spielberg's seminal film [E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial](/E.T._the_Extra-Terrestrial) that truly catapulted her to fame. Spielberg, recognizing her vivid imagination after she regaled him with tales of leading a punk rock band, cast her in the role. [31] *E.T.* became the highest-grossing film of the 1980s, cementing Barrymore as one of the most recognizable child actors of the era. Her performance earned her the [Young Artist Award](/Young_Artist_Award) for [Best Young Supporting Actress](/4th_Youth_in_Film_Awards) [23] [32] and a nomination for the [Rising Star Award](/BAFTA_Rising_Award) at the [British Academy Film Awards](/British_Academy_Film_Awards). Her early television presence was also notable; at just seven years old, she became the youngest person to [guest-host](/List_of_Saturday_Night_Live_guests) [Saturday Night Live](/Saturday_Night_Live) during its [eighth season](/Saturday_Night_Live_(season_8)). [33] Barrymore recalled the experience positively, noting that "nobody treated me like a kid there" and she felt like an equal member of the cast despite her age. [34]

In 1984, Barrymore took on the role of a young girl with [pyrokinesis](/Pyrokinesis) in the film adaptation of [Stephen King](/Stephen_King)'s novel [Firestarter](/Firestarter_(novel)). Her character was pursued by a clandestine government agency known as The Shop. That same year, she played a young girl navigating the divorce of her famous parents in [Irreconcilable Differences](/Irreconcilable_Differences), a performance that garnered her first [Golden Globe Award](/Golden_Globe_Award) nomination for [Best Supporting Actress](/Golden_Globe_Award_for_Best_Supporting_Actress_%E2%80%93_Motion_Picture). [23] [35] Renowned film critic [Roger Ebert](/Roger_Ebert) praised her portrayal in the [Chicago Sun-Times](/Chicago_Sun-Times), writing, "Barrymore is the right actress for this role precisely because she approaches it with such grave calm." [36] She further showcased her talent in the anthology horror film [Cat's Eye](/Cat%27s_Eye_(1985_film)), another adaptation of King's work. The film received positive reviews, and Barrymore earned another Young Artist Award nomination, this time for Best Leading Young Actress. [37]

### Teenage stardom (1986–1997)

The late 1980s saw Barrymore navigate a period of personal turmoil, resulting in intermittent acting roles. She appeared in the 1989 romance film [See You in the Morning](/See_You_in_the_Morning_(film)). While [Vincent Canby](/Vincent_Canby) of [The New York Times](/The_New_York_Times) critiqued the film's "fashionable phoniness," he singled out Barrymore's performance for praise. [38] In [Far from Home](/Far_from_Home_(1989_film)), she portrayed a teenager stranded in a remote desert town with her father. The film, however, failed to capture audience attention and was met with negative reviews, with some critics taking issue with the sexual undertones of her character. [39]

Barrymore's adolescent rebellion found expression both on screen and in the public eye. She starred as a disadvantaged teenager in [Poison Ivy](/Poison_Ivy_(1992_film)), a film that, despite being a [box-office bomb](/Box-office_bomb), found a significant audience on home video and [cable](/Cable_television). [1] [40] Her character, "Ivy," was later recognized by [Entertainment Weekly](/Entertainment_Weekly) as the sixth "bad girl" on their list of the top 26 such characters in film history. [41] At 17, Barrymore courted controversy when she posed nude with her then-fiancé, actor [Jamie Walters](/Jamie_Walters), for the cover and interior of the July issue of [Interview](/Interview_(magazine)) magazine. [42] [43]

In the film [Guncrazy](/Guncrazy), Barrymore played a teenager driven to kill her abusive stepfather. [35] *Variety* acknowledged her "impressive" performance, [44] and the role earned her a nomination for the [Golden Globe Award](/Golden_Globe_Award) for Best Actress in a Miniseries or Television Film. She also appeared in [No Place to Hide](/No_Place_to_Hide_(1993_film)) as the younger sister of a murdered ballerina, and in [Doppelganger](/Doppelganger_(1993_film)) as a writer stalked by her evil twin. Both films were critically panned and failed to resonate with audiences. [45] [46] [47] She then took a role in the Western film [Bad Girls](/Bad_Girls_(1994_film)), which depicted four former prostitutes on the run after committing a justifiable homicide and escaping prison. [Roger Ebert](/Roger_Ebert) offered a somber assessment in his review for the [Chicago Sun-Times](/Chicago_Sun-Times): "What a good idea, to make a Western about four tough women. And what a sad movie." [48]

Barrymore's decision to pose nude for the January 1995 issue of [Playboy](/Playboy) [49] [50] drew significant attention. Shortly thereafter, her godfather Steven Spielberg gifted her a quilt for her 20th birthday with a poignant message: "Cover yourself up." [23] Tucked within the quilt were doctored versions of her *Playboy* photos, digitally altered by Spielberg's art department to show her fully clothed. [51] Reflecting on this period, Barrymore later stated that she would not want her own child to make similar choices. [52]

A memorable appearance on the [Late Show with David Letterman](/Late_Show_with_David_Letterman) saw Barrymore impulsively climb onto the desk, flash her breasts to host [David Letterman](/David_Letterman), and plant a kiss on his cheek as a birthday gesture. [18] During this era, she also became the face of a series of [Guess?](/Guess_(clothing)) jeans advertisements. [53] By the late 1990s, Barrymore had successfully begun to redefine her public image, reaffirming her status as a highly bankable star. [1] [54]

In the film [Boys on the Side](/Boys_on_the_Side), Barrymore portrayed a pregnant woman seeking refuge from an abusive boyfriend. [55] The film achieved box office success and garnered positive critical reception. [56] In the superhero blockbuster [Batman Forever](/Batman_Forever), she played one of the henchwomen of the villain [Two-Face](/Two-Face), portrayed by [Tommy Lee Jones](/Tommy_Lee_Jones). [57] [58]

Barrymore in 1997

Barrymore made a memorable, albeit brief, appearance in Wes Craven's groundbreaking slasher film [Scream](/Scream_(1996_film)) (1996). Intrigued by the script, she proactively approached the production team to express her interest in a role. The producers seized the opportunity, initially casting her as the lead, [Sidney Prescott](/Sidney_Prescott). However, due to unforeseen scheduling conflicts, Barrymore ultimately portrayed the character [Casey Becker](/Casey_Becker) in a pivotal opening scene, with [Neve Campbell](/Neve_Campbell) stepping into the leading role. *Scream* was met with widespread critical acclaim and achieved significant commercial success, grossing $173 million worldwide. [60] [61] Barrymore's performance earned her a nomination for the [Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actress](/Saturn_Award_for_Best_Supporting_Actress). [62]

### Established career (1998–2008)

In the 1998 romantic comedy [The Wedding Singer](/The_Wedding_Singer), Barrymore starred as a waitress who falls for the titular character, played by [Adam Sandler](/Adam_Sandler). [63] *Variety* described the film as a "spirited, funny and warm saga" that cleverly showcased the actors' strengths in a fresh way. [64] With a budget of $18 million, the film achieved international success, grossing $123.3 million. [65] That same year, she also starred in [Home Fries](/Home_Fries_(film)), playing a pregnant woman who unknowingly develops feelings for the stepson of her baby's deceased father. [66] Barrymore then took on a leading role in the historical drama [Ever After](/Ever_After) (1998), a film inspired by the classic fairy tale [Cinderella](/Cinderella), which earned $98 million at the box office. [67] Roger Ebert commented on Barrymore's performance, noting her ability to "hold the screen and involve us in her characters." [68]

Barrymore lent her voice to the titular [anthropomorphic](/Anthropomorphic) [Jack Russell terrier](/Jack_Russell_terrier) in the Christmas television film [Olive, the Other Reindeer](/Olive,_the_Other_Reindeer), receiving a nomination for a [Primetime Emmy Award](/Primetime_Emmy_Award). [69] Following the establishment of her production company, [Flower Films](/Flower_Films), [70] Barrymore and her partner [Nancy Juvonen](/Nancy_Juvonen) produced the company's inaugural film, [Never Been Kissed](/Never_Been_Kissed). In this romantic comedy, Barrymore portrayed an insecure copy editor for the [Chicago Sun-Times](/Chicago_Sun-Times) who goes undercover as a high school student. While critical reviews were mixed, [CNN](/CNN) lauded Barrymore's contribution, stating, "There are two words which describe why this film works: Drew Barrymore. Her comedic timing and willingness to go all out in her quest for a laugh combine to make Never Been Kissed a gratifying movie-going experience." [71] The film proved to be a commercial success, grossing $84.5 million. [72] [73]

In the action-comedy [Charlie's Angels](/Charlie%27s_Angels_(2000_film)), Barrymore, alongside [Cameron Diaz](/Cameron_Diaz) and [Lucy Liu](/Lucy_Liu), starred as the titular trio of investigators. The film was a significant box office triumph, further solidifying Barrymore's influence as a producer through her company. [74] [23] [75] She also starred in [Riding in Cars with Boys], portraying a young mother whose life unravels due to a failed marriage to a drug-addicted husband, a role inspired by the real-life experiences of [Beverly Donofrio](/Beverly_Donofrio). [1] When the production of the ambitious indie film [Donnie Darko](/Donnie_Darko) faced financial challenges, Barrymore stepped in, providing crucial financing through her company and taking on the role of the title character's English teacher. Although the film's initial theatrical release was impacted by the events of [9/11](/9/11), it achieved significant [cult](/Cult_film) status upon its DVD release, sparking widespread online discussion and analysis of its complex narrative. [76]

Barrymore collaborated with [George Clooney](/George_Clooney) on his directorial debut, [Confessions of a Dangerous Mind](/Confessions_of_a_Dangerous_Mind_(film)), a biographical thriller based on the autobiography of television producer [Chuck Barris](/Chuck_Barris). She reprised her role as Dylan Sanders in the sequel [Charlie's Angels: Full Throttle](/Charlie%27s_Angels:_Full_Throttle) [1] [75] and later starred opposite [Ben Stiller](/Ben_Stiller) in the domestic comedy [Duplex](/Duplex_(film)). In collaboration with Flower Films and [Happy Madison Productions](/Happy_Madison_Productions), she starred in [50 First Dates](/50_First_Dates) as a woman with anterograde amnesia, alongside [Adam Sandler](/Adam_Sandler), who played a marine veterinarian. [78] [79] Critiquing Barrymore's performance in his review, Roger Ebert noted her "smiling, coy sincerity," describing the film as "ingratiating and lovable." [80] *50 First Dates* was a significant commercial success, earning US$120.9 million in North America and US$196.4 million worldwide. [81]

In the 2005 American remake of the 1997 British film [Fever Pitch](/Fever_Pitch_(1997_film)), Barrymore played the love interest of an immature schoolteacher, portrayed by [Jimmy Fallon](/Jimmy_Fallon). The film achieved modest success, grossing US$50 million worldwide, and was generally well-received by critics who praised the "charm and on-screen chemistry between [Fallon and Barrymore]." [82] Barrymore also lent her voice to the titular character in the 2006 animated film [Curious George](/Curious_George_(2006_film)), based on the beloved children's book series. Alongside [Hugh Grant](/Hugh_Grant), she starred in [Music and Lyrics](/Music_and_Lyrics), a romantic comedy centered on the evolving relationship between a washed-up pop star and an aspiring songwriter as they collaborate on a hit song. Released in February 2007, the film garnered largely positive reviews, with [The Washington Post](/The_Washington_Post) highlighting the "great" chemistry between the leads. [83] The film proved to be a commercial hit, grossing US$145 million globally. [84] [85]

Barrymore at the premiere for Music & Lyrics in 2007

In [Curtis Hanson](/Curtis_Hanson)'s poker drama [Lucky You](/Lucky_You_(film)), Barrymore played an aspiring singer who becomes the object of affection for a talented poker player. [86] [87] She also voiced the titular character in [Raja Gosnell](/Raja_Gosnell)'s family film [Beverly Hills Chihuahua](/Beverly_Hills_Chihuahua), portraying a pampered pet who gets dognapped in Mexico and must find her way home.

### Directorial debut and television roles (2009–2019)

Barrymore was part of the ensemble cast in the romantic comedy [He's Just Not That Into You](/He%27s_Just_Not_That_Into_You_(film)). While the film received mixed reviews, partly attributed to her limited screen time, [88] [89] [90] it achieved considerable commercial success, grossing US$178 million worldwide. [91] Her performance as [Edith Bouvier Beale](/Edith_Bouvier_Beale), the daughter of [Edith Ewing Bouvier Beale](/Edith_Ewing_Bouvier_Beale) (portrayed by [Jessica Lange](/Jessica_Lange)), in the HBO film [Grey Gardens](/Grey_Gardens_(2009_film)), based on the iconic 1975 documentary, was widely acclaimed. The television film garnered significant accolades, winning five [Primetime Emmy Awards](/Primetime_Emmy_Awards) and two [Golden Globe Awards](/Golden_Globe_Awards). [Peter Travers](/Peter_Travers) of [Rolling Stone](/Rolling_Stone) hailed Barrymore's performance as a "revelation." [92] For her work in *Grey Gardens*, Barrymore received an [Emmy Award](/Emmy_Award) nomination for [Outstanding Lead Actress in a Miniseries or a Movie](/Primetime_Emmy_Award_for_Outstanding_Lead_Actress_in_a_Miniseries_or_a_Movie), and secured the Golden Globe Award for [Best Actress – Miniseries or Television Film](/Golden_Globe_Award_for_Best_Actress_%E2%80%93_Miniseries_or_Television_Film) and the [Screen Actors Guild](/Screen_Actors_Guild) award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Television Movie or Miniseries.

Barrymore made her foray into directing with the film [Whip It](/Whip_It_(film)). The movie centers on a high school student ([Elliot Page](/Elliot_Page)) who rebels against her mother's expectations by joining an [Austin, Texas](/Austin,_Texas) [roller derby](/Roller_derby) league. [93] Barrymore collaborated closely with screenwriter [Shauna Cross](/Shauna_Cross) on script revisions, encouraging her to "avoid her story's tidier prospects, to make things 'more raw and open ended.'" [94] Despite a limited box office performance, the film was met with favorable reviews. [95] [96] According to review aggregator [Rotten Tomatoes](/Rotten_Tomatoes), critics concurred that her "directorial debut has enough charm, energy, and good-natured humor to transcend its many cliches." [97] [98] For her directorial effort, Barrymore received nominations for a Bronze Horse at the [Stockholm Film Festival](/Stockholm_Film_Festival) and the EDA Female Focus Award at the 2009 [Alliance of Women Film Journalists](/Alliance_of_Women_Film_Journalists) awards. In the 2009 drama [Everybody's Fine](/Everybody%27s_Fine_(2009_film)), Barrymore played the daughter of a recently widowed retiree, portrayed by [Robert De Niro](/Robert_De_Niro). [99] The film was a box office disappointment, [100] though Stephen Holden of [The New York Times](/The_New_York_Times) praised Barrymore's "ingenuous" performance in what he described as a "small role." [101] [102]

Barrymore starred alongside [Justin Long](/Justin_Long) in [Nanette Burstein](/Nanette_Burstein)'s 2010 film [Going the Distance](/Going_the_Distance_(2010_film)). The movie explores the challenges of a couple navigating a [long-distance relationship](/Long-distance_relationship) between New York City and San Francisco. It received generally mixed reviews, with critics noting it as "timelier and a little more honest than most romantic comedies." [103] [104] With a budget of US$32 million, [105] the film grossed US$40 million worldwide. [106]

On August 2, 2011, Barrymore directed the music video for the song "Our Deal" by the band [Best Coast](/Best_Coast), featuring a cast including [Chloë Grace Moretz](/Chlo%C3%AB_Grace_Moretz), [Miranda Cosgrove](/Miranda_Cosgrove), [Tyler Posey](/Tyler_Posey), [Donald Glover](/Donald_Glover), [Shailene Woodley](/Shailene_Woodley), and [Alia Shawkat](/Alia_Shawkat). [107] Barrymore starred in the 2012 biographical film [Big Miracle](/Big_Miracle), which chronicled the 1988 international effort known as [Operation Breakthrough](/Operation_Breakthrough) to rescue [gray whales](/Gray_whale) trapped in ice near [Point Barrow, Alaska](/Point_Barrow,_Alaska). [108] Her character, Rachel Kramer, was based on [Greenpeace](/Greenpeace) activist Cindy Lowry. [109] Despite a positive critical reception, [110] the film underperformed at the box office. [111]

[Toni Collette](/Toni_Collette) and Barrymore at the premiere for Miss You Already at the [2015 Toronto International Film Festival](/2015_Toronto_International_Film_Festival)
In the 2014 film [Blended](/Blended_(film)), Barrymore played a recently divorced woman who finds herself on vacation with a widower, played by [Adam Sandler](/Adam_Sandler). Film critic [James Berardinelli](/James_Berardinelli) criticized the film's "hit-and-miss humor" and remarked that "as [Sandler and Barrymore] are concerned, the third time is definitely not the charm," reflecting a general sentiment of lukewarm critical response. [112] [113] The film ultimately grossed US$128 million worldwide. [114] She starred alongside [Toni Collette](/Toni_Collette) in [Miss You Already](/Miss_You_Already) (2015), portraying two lifelong friends whose bond is tested when one begins a family and the other faces a serious illness. The film received praise from reviewers, though it had a limited theatrical release. [115] [116]

Barrymore took on a leading role in the [Netflix](/Netflix) original series [Santa Clarita Diet](/Santa_Clarita_Diet), playing a real estate agent who undergoes a transformation into a [zombie](/Zombie) and develops a taste for human flesh. Alongside co-star [Timothy Olyphant](/Timothy_Olyphant), Barrymore served as an executive producer for the [single-camera](/Single-camera) series. [117] The show was met with a favorable reception upon its premiere, [118] [119] [120] with [Rolling Stone](/Rolling_Stone_(magazine)) attributing much of the series' humor to Barrymore's "uncrushable charm." The publication further noted, "The show is a welcome comeback for Barrymore, the eternally beloved grunge-era wild thing—it's not just her big move into TV, but her first high-profile performance anywhere in years. In a way, it circles back to the roles she was doing in the early [90s], playing deadly vixens in flicks like Guncrazy or Doppelganger." [121]

### The Drew Barrymore Show and expansion (2020–present)

Barrymore starred in [Jamie Babbit](/Jamie_Babbit)'s 2020 film [The Stand In](/The_Stand_In_(2020_film)), which was initially slated to premiere at the [Tribeca Film Festival](/Tribeca_Film_Festival) in April 2020 but was ultimately cancelled due to the [COVID-19 pandemic](/COVID-19_pandemic). [122] [123] [124] On September 14, 2020, Barrymore launched her syndicated daytime talk show, [The Drew Barrymore Show](/The_Drew_Barrymore_Show). [125] She made a guest appearance on [Martha Knows Best](/Martha_Knows_Best) on December 4, 2020. [126] On March 11, 2021, Barrymore announced an indefinite hiatus from acting, [127] focusing instead on her other ventures. She co-authored a cookbook with chef Pilar Valdes titled *Rebel Homemaker*, which became a *New York Times* bestseller. [128] [129] In June 2021, she launched *Drew Magazine*, a quarterly lifestyle publication released by [Bauer Media](/Bauer_Media) USA. [130] Her significant influence and impact were recognized when *Time* magazine included her in their list of the [100 most influential people in the world](/Time_100) in 2023. [2]

In September 2023, Barrymore announced her intention to continue her syndicated talk show despite the ongoing WGA strike, stating via social media, "I own this choice." [131] While SAG had clarified that as a talk show host she was not obligated to strike, her show proceeded without unionized writing staff. Reports emerged of audience members supporting the Writers Guild being removed from the taping and having their WGA pins confiscated. [132] In the wake of this controversy, the [National Book Foundation](/National_Book_Foundation) removed Barrymore from her role as host of the upcoming 74th [National Book Awards](/National_Book_Award). [133] [134] Barrymore issued an apology via an Instagram video later that week, admitting, "I have nothing I can do or say in this moment to make it OK." [135] [136] [137] [138] The apology video was subsequently deleted from her account following criticism. [139] [137] [138] On September 17th, Barrymore announced on Instagram that she would be postponing the premiere of her talk show until the strike concluded, stating, "I have listened to everyone, and I am making the decision to pause the show's premiere until the strike is over." She added, "I have no words to express my deepest apologies to anyone I have hurt, and, of course, to our incredible team who works on the show and has made it what it is today." [5] [140] [141] A spokesperson for CBS Media Ventures expressed support for her decision, stating, "We support Drew's decision to pause the show's return and understand how complex and difficult this process has been for her." [142]

In May 2024, it was announced that a revival of the game show [Hollywood Squares](/Hollywood_Squares) would be produced by [CBS](/CBS), with Barrymore serving as a co-executive producer and taking on the role of the center square. [143] The series, hosted by [Nate Burleson](/Nate_Burleson), is set to premiere on January 16, 2025. On February 24, 2025, the revival was officially renewed for a second season. [144]

## Media image

Barrymore became a spokesperson and model for [CoverGirl](/CoverGirl) Cosmetics in 2007. [145] In February 2015, she joined Queen Latifah and [Taylor Swift](/Taylor_Swift) as one of the faces of the brand. Esi Eggleston Bracey, vice president and general manager of CoverGirl Cosmetics North America, stated that Barrymore "emulates the iconic image of CoverGirl with her fresh, natural beauty and energetic yet authentic spirit." Barrymore's involvement extended beyond simply endorsing the product; she also contributed creatively to the advertising campaigns. [146] In 2007, she topped *People* magazine's annual list of the 100 Most Beautiful People. [147] She was also selected as the new face for the [Gucci](/Gucci) jewelry line. [148] [149] Barrymore signed with the modeling agency [IMG Models](/IMG_Models) in New York City and has also served as a spokeswoman for Crocs.

In May 2007, Barrymore was appointed Ambassador Against Hunger for the United Nations [World Food Programme](/World_Food_Programme), [150] [151] later donating $1 million to the cause. [75] [152] As a guest photographer for a series titled "They Shoot New York" in [a magazine](/Time_Out_(magazine)), she appeared on the cover holding a [Pentax K1000](/Pentax_K1000) film camera. She expressed a desire to exhibit her photography, having documented the previous decade of her life with her Pentax camera. [153] [154]

Barrymore launched a women's fashion line called Dear Drew in the fall of 2017, in collaboration with [Amazon.com](/Amazon.com), [155] and opened a pop-up shop for the brand in New York City in November of that year. [156] In January 2024, she assumed the role of Chief Gifting Officer for [Etsy](/Etsy). [157]

## Personal life

At the age of 16, in 1991, Barrymore was briefly engaged to Leland Hayward III, the grandson of producer [Leland Hayward](/Leland_Hayward). [158]

From 1992 to 1993, Barrymore, then 17, was in a relationship with 23-year-old [Jamie Walters](/Jamie_Walters). [159] Walters proposed to her with a diamond ring while they were in a 1967 [Chevrolet Chevelle](/Chevrolet_Chevelle), and they planned to marry in the spring of 1993. [160] Both Walters and Barrymore have tattoos of each other's names: Walters has her name inked on his upper right shoulder blade in the form of a [Christian cross](/Christian_cross), while Barrymore has his name, along with her mother's name, incorporated into a banner flown by a [cherub](/Cherub) on her lower back. [161] [160] In 2023, during an interview with [Tori Spelling](/Tori_Spelling) on her talk show (Spelling had played Walters' love interest on [Beverly Hills, 90210](/Beverly_Hills,_90210)), Barrymore spoke fondly of Walters. [162]

In early 1994, at the age of 19, Barrymore began dating Jeremy Thomas, a 31-year-old business owner from [Wales](/Wales). Thomas owned The Room, a bar on [Cahuenga Boulevard](/Cahuenga_Boulevard), where he reportedly allowed Barrymore to drink despite her being underage, a time when she was already undergoing intermittent treatment for [alcoholism](/Alcoholism). [163] On March 20, 1994, after only six weeks of dating, the couple impulsively married at approximately 5:30 am at The Room, hiring a 24-hour minister to officiate. [164] [165] [166] Barrymore wore a simple white slip dress and combat boots for the ceremony. [163] Barrymore and Thomas separated just 19 days later, and she filed for divorce less than two months after the wedding, alleging that Thomas had married her for her wealth and a [green card](/Green_card). [1] [18] [164] Their divorce was finalized in 1995. [165] In a later interview that year, Barrymore described Thomas to [Rolling Stone](/Rolling_Stone) as "the [Devil](/Devil)." [165]

In late 1994, Barrymore began a relationship with [Hole](/Hole_(band)) guitarist [Eric Erlandson](/Eric_Erlandson). [167] She later dated MTV host and comedian [Tom Green](/Tom_Green), whom she met in 1999. They became engaged in July 2000 and married a year later. [1] Together, they appeared in [Charlie's Angels](/Charlie%27s_Angels_(2000_film)) and Green's directorial debut, [Freddy Got Fingered](/Freddy_Got_Fingered). Green filed for divorce in December 2001, and it was finalized on October 15, 2002. [168] [169]

In 2002, Barrymore began dating [The Strokes](/The_Strokes) drummer [Fabrizio Moretti](/Fabrizio_Moretti), whom she had met at one of their concerts. [1] Their relationship concluded in January 2007. [75] [170] She subsequently dated actor [Justin Long](/Justin_Long), [171] but they separated in July 2008. [172]

In February 2011, Barrymore started dating Will Kopelman, an art consultant and the son of [Arie L. Kopelman](/Arie_L._Kopelman), who previously held the position of [chief operating officer](/Chief_operating_officer) at the renowned French fashion house [Chanel](/Chanel). [173] Kopelman proposed to Barrymore in [Sun Valley, Idaho](/Sun_Valley,_Idaho) in December of that year during a [Christmas](/Christmas) vacation. Media outlets reported their engagement in January 2012. [174] [175] [176] They married on June 2, 2012, in a garden-themed [Jewish ceremony](/Jewish_wedding) held at her home in [Montecito, California](/Montecito,_California). Barrymore wore a custom Chanel wedding gown. [177] [178] Barrymore gave birth to their first child three months later, followed by their second child in 2014. [179] [180] [181] During her marriage to Kopelman, Barrymore expressed an interest in [converting to Judaism](/Converting_to_judaism), the faith of her husband, calling it a "beautiful faith," though she did not formally convert. [182] Barrymore announced her separation from Kopelman on April 2, 2016. They filed for divorce on July 15, 2016, and it was finalized on August 3, 2016. [183] [184] [185] In 2020, Barrymore told *People* magazine that she had no intention of marrying again. [186] Kopelman later married Vogue director Alexandra "Allie" Michler in 2021, and Barrymore has spoken positively of her relationship with Michler, describing her as a wonderful stepmother. [187] In 2023, Barrymore relocated to [Manhattan](/Manhattan) to ensure her children could remain closer to Kopelman. [188] [189]

Barrymore practices [meditation](/Meditation). [190]

In a 2003 interview with *New Woman* magazine, Barrymore stated: "Do I like women sexually? Yeah, I do. Totally. I have always considered myself bisexual. I love a woman's body. I think a woman and a woman together are beautiful, just as a man and a woman together are beautiful. Being with a woman is like exploring your own body, but through someone else." She further added, "I don’t think I could ever just solely be with a woman…It’s just not enough for me." [191] [192] [193]

Barrymore serves as the godmother to [Frances Bean Cobain](/Frances_Bean_Cobain), the daughter of musicians [Kurt Cobain](/Kurt_Cobain) and [Courtney Love](/Courtney_Love). [194]

Barrymore adheres to a [plant-based diet](/Plant-based_diet) [195] and is credited with encouraging rapper [Cardi B](/Cardi_B) to explore [veganism](/Veganism). [196] [197] [198]

## Acting credits and accolades

### Main articles: [Drew Barrymore filmography](/Drew_Barrymore_filmography) and [List of awards and nominations received by Drew Barrymore](/List_of_awards_and_nominations_received_by_Drew_Barrymore)

Barrymore's filmography boasts a worldwide box office gross exceeding US$2.3 billion. [The Hollywood Reporter](/The_Hollywood_Reporter) ranked her among the highest-paid actresses in 2006, commanding salaries of $10 to $12 million per film. [199]

Barrymore holds the distinction of being the youngest person to host [Saturday Night Live](/Saturday_Night_Live), making her debut as a host on November 20, 1982, at the age of seven. This record remains unbroken as of 2024. [200] [201] She hosted the show for the fifth time on February 3, 2007, becoming only the second female host, after [Candice Bergen](/Candice_Bergen), to achieve this milestone. [75] In 2009, she hosted for a sixth time, making her the first woman to reach this number. [202]

In recognition of her early career achievements, Barrymore was honored by the [Young Artist Foundation](/Young_Artist_Award) in 1999 with its [Former Child Star "Lifetime Achievement" Award](/Young_Artist_Former_Child_Star_Lifetime_Achievement_Award) for her significant contributions to the [film industry](/Film_industry) as a child actress. [203] In 2004, she was further recognized for her contributions to cinema with a star on the [Hollywood Walk of Fame](/Hollywood_Walk_of_Fame), located at 6925 [Hollywood Boulevard](/Hollywood_Boulevard). [204]

## Bibliography

Following a highly publicized childhood marked by struggles with drug and alcohol abuse, Barrymore released her autobiography, *Little Girl Lost*, which achieved bestseller status on the *New York Times* list. [1] In 2015, [E. P. Dutton](/E._P._Dutton) published *Wildflower*, a collection of Barrymore's autobiographical essays, which also became a bestseller. She narrated the [audiobook](/Audiobook) version of *Wildflower*. [205] [206]

